Student debt forgiveness is a policy position that has got a lot of buzz recently. 
Joe Biden [has promised to give up to $10,000 to anyone with student debt.](https://www.cnbc.com/2021/01/08/student-loan-forgiveness-could-be-more-likely-but-challenges-remain-.html)
And other politicians have urged him to give as much as $50,000 per person.

https://www.forbes.com/sites/wesleywhistle/2020/10/20/how-joe-biden-would-help-low-income-college-students/?sh=7648661c4f0b

While browsing reddit's front page recently, I came across this tweet on the subreddit "r murderedbyAOC":

> tweet goes heres

The format of twitter forces people to condense complex arguments down into simplistic hot takes, so I don't want this to be read as a "dunking on" this particular politician.

But what's a reddit post if the take isn't at least a little bit spicy? So instead of just arguing against student debt forgiveness in the abstract, 
I'll try to frame this as an argument that "I got screwed and so should you" is a sensible argument when applied to the context of *student* debt.



30k on average
https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/education/2021/01/08/student-loan-forgiveness-biden-freeze-interest-payment/6602401002/


